	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=145263><span id=Scholar>lunaticfringesk</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>305 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.95]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Im not so sure that I agree that &quot;more melee gear has str/sta/dex over int&quot; is a true statement.&nbsp;&nbsp;Many would argue that sta is one of, if not the, hardest stat to increase.  There is probably at least some truth to that statment from what I have seen and experienced.<br><br>If you look at Thurg, PoG, Kael or Skyshrine armor, int is buffed over substantially all other stats (only str is higher in substantially all cases; interestingly enough, agi was the least buffed with these armor sets).  Yes, this is higher end armor, but it illustrates that int is not as hard to raise at all through melee gear.  Further, there are quite a few int buff items out there that are fairly cheap and easy to acquire.  Hell, Neptunis could probably name 20 off the top of his head.  =)  I could name quite a few, but I think he is far more versed on some of the lower end items than I am.<br><br>Im not sure, however, that I understand what you are questioning from my original post though.  If you are saying that certain high int races hold an advantage over the larger, less int races, as int is a harder stat to increase than the others, I would strongly disagree.  Int doesnt seem all that difficult to raise firstly, and mana producing items that you receive later in life is generally more efficient way of increasing your mana pool, if that was your goal (which I seldom would understand anyways). <br><br>As far as what items to get, stats to buff, etc. I would probably just focus on AC and HP and let the stats fall where they do.  That is not a hard rule mind you, but rather a guideline that is more often appropriate then not.<br><br>Lunatic</p>&nbsp;<br> </t